I would like an option on export space to save only the last version of all documents and attachments.  I would expect the restore operation to restore all the pages and attachments as version 1.  This would be very helpful for populating a secondary site with a clean copy of data.  For instance, I might need to remove confidential data before exporting or there may be preliminary data that I don't want users to see in the history.  It also make the exported zip file smaller especially when large attachments are involved.  I know there are some SQL based work arounds that can help clean up a space after the fact.  These are difficult and error prone.

The notation guide is arguably the most important document that new and existing users have yet we have hardly touched it since the early days.

Firstly, we need two versions of the notation guide:
 
 1. One for Wiki Markup mode;

 2. And secondly for WYSIWYG editing mode (you can still use macros and advanced formatting in WYSIWG) - currently the markup guide is only accessible from the wiki markup mode.

This issue is not based on a comprehensive review of the notation guide but general areas of improvement would be to ensure:

 * the notation guide is written in a way that makes sense to lay business users;

 * the notation guide is thoroughly reviewed and broken up into more logical sections and sub-sections  - e.g. columns (currently addressed under 'tables') should be addressed in a new section called layout;

 * the notation guide is written in a more concisely and obvious fashion. An obvious improvement would be to ensure each entry has a name, description and an example for each (both markup example and rendered example). A four column table rather than a two column table maybe be necessary. Using examples to name each notation guide entry, as is currently the case, is not sufficient. Let me elaborate on this point by way of example:

  - "bq. Some block quoted text" in the Text Formatting category should be named "Block Quote", a description provided and a example of the markup and the rendered result provided;

 * the notation guide also needs to completely up to date.

